6. One likely real issue in your case
For your 8A -> OK example, I strongly suspect this:
The global consumer QM map is being built from app_id
but the consumer identity you need may not line up consistently across all local rows.
So instead of only mapping by app_id, build both:
app_id → local QMs
ConsumerName → local QMs
Then use whichever matches.
Minimal fix
Replace the global map block with this:
Python
# --------------------------------------------------------
    # GLOBAL CONSUMER EVIDENCE MAPS
    # Use full dataset evidence, not only current grouped rows
    # --------------------------------------------------------
    app_local_qm_map: Dict[str, set] = {}
    consumer_name_local_qm_map: Dict[str, set] = {}

    local_df_for_map = df[df["q_type_norm"].str.contains("Local", case=False, na=False)].copy()

    for _, row in local_df_for_map.iterrows():
        app_id = normalize_text(row.get("app_id", ""))
        consumer_name_val = normalize_text(row.get("ConsumerName", ""))
        qm_name = normalize_text(row.get("queue_manager_name", ""))

        if app_id and qm_name:
            app_local_qm_map.setdefault(app_id, set()).add(qm_name)

        if consumer_name_val and qm_name:
            consumer_name_local_qm_map.setdefault(consumer_name_val, set()).add(qm_name)
Then replace:
Python
global_consumer_local_qms = sorted(app_local_qm_map.get(consumer_app, set()))
with:
Python
global_consumer_local_qms = sorted(
            set(app_local_qm_map.get(consumer_app, set())) |
            set(consumer_name_local_qm_map.get(consumer_name, set()))
        )
This is likely the missing piece if 8A->OK still does not move forward.
